With compute as a service, AWS takes care of the physical infrastructure (secured data centers, servers, network connections, and others).
AWS offers three types of compute options at the fundamental level – instances (virtual machines), containers, and serverless.


# 1 Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud

![](image/Pasted%20image%2020231010195246.png)


Amazon EC2 is a web service that provides secure and resizable compute capacity in the cloud, allowing you to provision virtual servers called Amazon EC2 instances.

With Amazon EC2 you can: 
• Provision and launch one or more EC2 instances in minutes 
• Stop or shut down EC2 instances when you finish running a workload 
• Pay by the hour or second for each instance type (minimum of 60 seconds)


You can create and manage EC2 instances through the AWS Management Console, AWS Command Line Interface (CLI), AWS software development kits (SDKs), or through automation tools and infrastructure orchestration services.


When you launch an EC2 instance, the first setting is to select an Amazon Machine Image (AMI). 


![](image/Pasted%20image%2020231010213109.png)


When you launch an EC2 instance, you first specify an Amazon Machine Image (AMI). An AMI includes the operating system, storage mapping, architecture type, launch permissions, and any additional preinstalled software applications. Then the AMI is copied to the root device volume. You can use a single AMI to launch multiple EC2 instances with the same configurations.

AWS supports Linux, macOS, Windows, and other operating systems.
For AMIs, you can: 
• Create your own 
• Use available AWS AMIs 
• Purchase from AWS Marketplace

Reference To learn more about AMI, refer to the AMI online user guide: https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/AMIs.html.



![](image/Pasted%20image%2020231010213142.png)

Amazon EC2 offers several instance types.
Selecting an instance type depends on your workload and application requirements. These requirement types are categorized as general purpose, compute optimized, memory optimized, accelerated computing, and storage optimized.

General purpose instances provide a balance of compute, memory, and networking resources. They can be used for workloads such as web application servers, containerized microservices, distributed data stores, and development environments.

Compute optimized instances are ideal for compute-bound applications that benefit from high-performance processors. These instances can be used for workloads like scientific modeling, batch processing, distributed analytics, high performance computing (HPC), and machine learning.

Memory optimized instances deliver fast performance for workloads that process large datasets in memory. They are used for memory-intensive applications such as high-performance databases, distributed web-scale in-memory caches, real-time big data analytics, and more.

Accelerated computing instances use hardware accelerators or coprocessors to perform functions such as floating-point number calculations, graphics processing, or data pattern matching more efficiently than is possible with conventional CPUs. Examples of these functions include 3D visualizations, graphics-intensive remote workstations, 3D rendering, application streaming, video encoding, and more.

Storage optimized instances are designed for workloads that require sequential read and write access to large datasets on local storage. Examples of workloads suitable for storage optimized instances include NoSQL databases, in-memory databases, scale-out transactional databases, data warehousing, Elasticsearch, and analytics



![](image/Pasted%20image%2020231010213228.png)


Here are some examples of Amazon EC2 instance types:

- General purpose: M5 instances, powered by Intel Xeon Platinum 8175M processors, provide a balance of compute, memory, and network resources.
- Compute optimized: C5 instances are optimized for compute-intensive workloads and deliver cost-effective high performance at a low price per compute ratio. Memory optimized: R6g instances, powered by an ARM-based AWS Graviton2 processor, deliver better performance for memory-intensive applications.
- Accelerated computing: P4 instances, the latest generation of GPU-based instances, provide highest performance for machine learning training and high-performance cloud computing.
- Storage optimized: D2 instances feature up to 48 TB of HDD-based local storage, deliver high disk throughput, and offer the lowest price per disk throughput performance on Amazon EC2.

An EC2 instance transitions between different states from the moment you create it all the way through to when you terminate it.
• When you first launch an instance from an AMI or start it from a stopped state, it goes into the pending state. You will not be billed at this state.
• Once AWS has copied the AMI into the root volume and allocated necessary network components, the instance enters the running state. The instance is ready for use, and you will be billed.
• You can reboot the instance at any time.
• When you stop the instance, this puts the instance into the stopped state, and it cannot be used. You can start the instance again at any time. You will not be billed in the stopped state. This is similar to when you shut down your laptop. When you put the instance into stop-hibernate, the instance enters the stopped state, but saves the last information or content into memory, so that the start process is faster. Once running, you can resume from where you stopped.
• From the running or stopped state, if you are done with using your instance, you can proceed to terminate the instance. In the terminated state, the instance is permanently deleted and cannot be started. All data in the instance is deleted unless you have saved the data at external storage.

Amazon EC2 offers a variety of pricing options to address different workload scenarios.
To use EC2 instances for free, Amazon EC2 offers a Free Tier option. This option includes 750 hours of Linux and Windows t2.micro instances (t3.micro for the AWS Regions in which t2.micro is unavailable) each month for one year.

For uninterrupted and unpredictable workloads, with predictable pricing and no upfront payment, Amazon EC2 offers the On-Demand Instances option. With this option, you only pay for compute capacity by the hour or the second depending on the instance. For a Linux/Ubuntu instance, you pay by the second after the first minute and for Windows and Mac instances, you pay by the hour.

For applications that have flexible start and end times, Amazon EC2 offers the Spot Instances option. With this option, you save up to 90 percent off of the On-Demand price.

For a flexible pricing model that offers low prices on Amazon EC2 and AWS Fargate, in exchange for a commitment to a consistent amount of usage ($/hour) for a 1-or 3-year term, Amazon EC2 offers Savings Plans.

For applications with steady state usage that might require reserved capacity, Amazon EC2 offers the Reserved Instances option. With this option, you save up to 75 percent compared to On-Demand Instance pricing with a 1-or 3-year term commitment.
Billing by the second is also available for Reserved and Spot Instances

# 2 AWS container services

![](image/Pasted%20image%2020231010213641.png)

A container is a standardized unit that can package your application’s code and dependencies. The container can run on any operating system (OS). With containers, applications can run the same on any machine without compatibility issues, with predictable behavior, and with more efficient maintenance and deployments.

An example of a containerization platform is a Docker engine.

To create, package, deploy, and run containers, you can use Dockers. A Docker is a software development platform used to deploy applications. When compared to virtual machines (VMs), containers:
• Share the same OS and kernel as the host they are deployed on 
• Take seconds to start 

An example of a virtualization platform is a hypervisor. 


Virtual machines have two types of hypervisors:
• Type-1: Native or bare-metal hypervisors, which run directly on the host server to control the hardware and manage guest OS
• Type-2: Hosted hypervisors, which run on a conventional OS

Generally, organizations can readily manage a few containers. As more containers are added on multiple EC2 instances across Availability Zones, managing container deployments, in addition to container and instance failures, can become challenging. To address this, AWS offers the containers orchestration services.

![](image/Pasted%20image%2020231010213849.png)

AWS offers Amazon Elastic Container Service (Amazon ECS) and Amazon Elastic Kubernetes Service (EKS) for container orchestration.
Amazon ECS is a highly scalable and high-performance container management system that helps customers spin up new containers and manage them across EC2 instances. Amazon ECS supports Docker containers.
In order to manage your containers, you have to install an open source Amazon ECS container agent on your EC2 instances. This agent is referred to as a container instance. You can run this agent on both Linux and Windows AMIs. Amazon ECS uses API calls to control Docker-enabled applications.
Amazon EKS provides the flexibility to start, run, and scale Kubernetes applications in the AWS Cloud or on-premises. Kubernetes is an open source platform for managing containerized applications. It is portable and extensible.
With Amazon EKS, you will be able to provide highly available and secure clusters. It automates patching, node provisioning, and updates.

# 3 Serverless


![](image/Pasted%20image%2020231010214056.png)

Fargate : runs container, whithout you as customer going to manage the underlying servers
Aws lambda:  run code piece
Serverless compute:  pay it only when the code is running

The benefits of serverless compute are: 
• No servers to provision or manage 
• It scales with usage 
• Customers only pay for resources they have used 
• Availability and fault tolerance are built in


AWS offers AWS Fargate and AWS Lambda as serverless compute options.
AWS Fargate is a serverless compute engine for containers. It supports both Amazon ECS and Amazon EKS architecture.
AWS Fargate allocates the right amount of compute, reducing the need to manage EC2 instances, cluster capacity, and scaling.
In order to deploy applications without managing EC2 instances or containers, you can use AWS Lambda.
Reference To learn more about serverless compute, visit the Serverless on AWS website: https://aws.amazon.com/serverless/

AWS Lambda is a compute service that helps you run code without provisioning or managing servers. You pay only for the compute time you consume – you incur no charges when your code is not running.
With AWS Lambda, you can run code for virtually any type of application or backend service, all with zero administration. You need only to upload your code and AWS Lambda manages everything required to run and scale your code with high availability. You can set up your code to automatically launch from other AWS services or call it directly from any web or mobile app.
Before using AWS Lambda, you must have an understanding of the following key Lambda concepts:
• Event source – what invokes the call 
• Language choice 
• Execution environment – permissions and resources


The code you run on AWS Lambda uploads as a Lambda function. Each function has associated configuration information, such as its name, description, entry point, and resource requirements. The code must be written in a “stateless” style, that is, it should assume that there is no affinity to the underlying compute infrastructure. Local file system access, child processes, and similar artifacts might not extend beyond the lifetime of the request, and any persistent state should be stored in Amazon S3, Amazon DynamoDB, or another internet-available storage service. Lambda functions can also can include libraries, including native ones.



Reference For more information, see the AWS Lambda website: https://aws.amazon.com/lambda/.


# 4 Knowledge Check 

Which of the following is true about serverless compute? 
A. Customers must provision and manage servers.
B. Customers must manually scale the serverless resources.
C. Serverless applications have built-in service integrations. 
D. Customers must manage availability and fault tolerance.

The correct response option is C. Serverless applications have built-in service integrations.
Explanation: Serverless applications have built-in service integrations, so customers can focus on building their application instead of configuring it.

Which of the following statements about containers and virtual machines is correct?
A. Virtual machines share an operating system kernel. 
B. Containers share an operating system kernel. 
C. Virtual machines must use the same operating system as the hypervisor. 
D. Containers each have their own kerne

The correct response option is B. Containers share an operating system kernel.
Explanation: Containers are designed to be lightweight compared to virtual machines. Containers share an operating system kernel with the host operating system, but they have their own copies of any libraries they require to be self contained at the software level.

What does an Amazon EC2 instance type indicate?
A. Instance family and instance size 
B. Instance placement and instance size 
C. Instance tenancy and instance billing 
D. Instance AMI and networking speed

The correct response option is A. Instance family and instance size.

Explanation: Amazon EC2 provides a wide selection of instance types optimized to fit different use cases. Instance types comprise varying combinations of CPU, memory, storage, and networking capacity and give you the flexibility to choose the appropriate mix of resources for your applications. Each instance type includes one or more instance sizes, allowing you to scale your resources to the requirements of your target workload.
